It's not just Hollywood actresses but in all work environments; the two journalists are determined to make the struggle worth it and enforce the #MeToo movement 
The law rarely takes all victims stories seriously, even the newspapers bury the stories that need to be heard, there's a whole machine operating protecting abusers, for women it's a constant battle to survive no women wants their daughters to grow up in a world where being taken advantage of is okay, most just want their voice back, even actresses get blackballed and ultimately shut out of their professions because of the claims they make getting dismissed entirely, using a direct quote of the opposite sex labels you a victim, the silence is most angering given that not one person is willing to speak up 
The movie is a deep dive into investigative surgery opening up the painful truth, journalism itself is often under siege but the truth is more important 
The movie works being direct, raw, honest and doesn't pull any punches 
It stinks so many women suffer in the workplace not just the world of entertainment Takes a lot of courage to talk about the trauma that goes on behind closed curtains but even harder to actually prove it 
This film realistically gives us a sense of how an investigation is built, sources being confirmed and protected, and documents uncovered 
It's also more than just putting a predator away; it's also about other things 
It is about the rage of women compelled to be silenced for years, the empathy borne out of shared experience and existence 
This plays more like a procedural and prolly would've served better as a streaming feature like Amazon prime video or HBO Max

But Mulligan and Kazan are pitch perfect as two women getting to the core of the real story and exposing all the hidden facets for real change

This will be a film one day I will show to my daughter. I started to work in the film industry during my mid-20s. After 5 years of hard work, I was finally making it into these so-called A-list film festivals with my work. It was all super exciting, the renowned filmmakers, influential producers, celebrities, red carpets, fancy parties etc. I was so eager to go there, make connections and pitch my work. But reality crushed me hard... Even though nothing worse than sexual harassment happened to me, it was almost enough to crush my passion. I even doubted it was maybe how I acted that made these people I was intending to work with say or do things inappropriately. I began to hate what I do. Also, I didn't think I could share any of this with anyone. Then MeToo happened, and I realized I was not at all alone in this experience. MeToo gave me my voice back and guided me back to my passion. MeToo made my world so different now as someone in my mid-30s, still trying to chase after my dream. It will also make a much better world for my daughter. For all of that, I am forever grateful for these women in this film!

I think this film may have come a little too late. So much has happened since fallout of Weinstein that so many have become disillusioned by the MeToo movement. From the prioritizing of young attractive, upper class white women over others, to the weaponizing of MeToo allegations for political and/or personal reasons, to the delegitimatizing of due process, etc. I think it's safe to say that the MeToo wave doesn't have the same hold on our culture as it did back in 2017 and I think a lot of people don't want to go back to 2017. And yes, sexual harassment and abuse is still a problem but how we see and talk about these problems are less black and white then it was just a few years ago. 

This film may be a box office hit and it may be really good film, but I just don't believe it would be as culturally significant as it would have been if it was realized a couple years earlier. I honestly think people are ready to evolve beyond the MeToo phenomenon into a nuanced and sophisticated cultural landscape.
